T1  - The Fisher hypothesis and the forecastability and persistence of inflation
AU  - Barsky, Robert B.
JO  - Journal of Monetary Economics
VL  - 19
IS  - 1
SP  - 3
EP  - 24
PY  - 1987
DA  - 1987/01/01/
SN  - 0304-3932
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3932(87)90026-2
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304393287900262
AB  - For the period 1860 to 1939, the simple correlation of the U.S. commercial paper rate with the contemporaneous inflation rate is −0.17. The corresponding correlation for the period 1950 to 1979 is 0.71. This paper attributes this apparent change in the Fisher relation to differences in the stochastic process of inflation, rather than a change in any structural relationship between interest rates and expected inflation. Contrary to recent claims in the literature, there is little evidence of inflation non-neutrality in data from the pre-World War I period.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Tobin's Q and financial policy
AU  - Chirinko, Robert S.
JO  - Journal of Monetary Economics
VL  - 19
IS  - 1
SP  - 69
EP  - 87
PY  - 1987
DA  - 1987/01/01/
SN  - 0304-3932
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3932(87)90029-8
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304393287900298
AB  - Recent research in macroeconomics has emphasized the importance of linking the financial and real sectors and working with optimizing models. Tobin's Q model of investment would appear to provide a framework satisfying these two criteria. In contrast to the original presentation of the Q model, the formal development has not recognized that the firm actively participates in a number of financial markets; in this broader context, Q may be an uninformative and possibly misleading signal for investment expenditures. We then endeavor to turn this negative theoretical result to positive advantage in resolving a number of empirical problems with Q models.
ER  - 

